Alpine Term

This is an application for Android OS running the Alpine Linux distribution in emulated x86_64 machine. Basically a compound of terminal emulator and headless build of the QEMU.

Inspired by Termux and UserLAnd applications.

User interface

Context menu

The context menu can be shown by long pressing anywhere on the terminal. It provides menu entries for:

  • Opening VNC connection. Available only if RealVNC Viewer is installed.
  • Copying or pasting text from clipboard.
  • Showing this help page.
  • Opening URL selector dialog.
  • Sharing text from the terminal to other apps.
  • Resetting the terminal state if it got messed up.
  • Selecting a color scheme of the terminal.
  • Checkbox to control whether bell characters should be ignored.

Navigation drawer

The navigation drawer is revealed by swiping inwards from the left part of screen.

It contains few additional elements:

  1. The list of sessions: click on a session to open.
  2. The button to toggle visibility of a touch keyboard.
    Long press will toggle the extra keys row (3).

Notification

While Alpine Term is running, it displays a notification which can be expanded by a pinch-zooming or a single-finger glide gestures to expose action for toggling wake lock to prevent deviceâ€™s CPU going into sleep mode.

Clicking on the notification will open the current terminal session.

Extra keys row

Alpine Term provides a row which contains some keys frequently used to interact with the command line. It can be toggled by either a long press on the keyboard button located on drawer or by Volume Up+Q and Volume Up+K key combinations.

Swiping up certain keys will expose the alternate ones. Particularly:

  • - will show a key for _
  • | will show a key for &

Text input field

Terminal does not support advanced features of the touch keyboards like a predictive input or swipe typing. As workaround, application provide a special text input field where all these features work correctly. It can be accessed by swiping the extra keys row to the left side.

Getting started

Terminal

Application emulates a subset of the X Window System (xterm) terminal. Its capabilities should be enough for most of the available command line programs.

Terminal acts as client to the serial line exposed by virtual machine. As result, virtual machine is not aware of current state of the console. You may observe visual glitches such as displaced or disappeared text when changing font size.

Use utility â€˜resizeâ€™ to make sure that console size matches the size of screen. If terminal was messed up, use the utility â€˜resetâ€™ which will clean screen and reset terminal to initial state.

Terminal is sensitive to taps and gestures. For example, pinch-zooming will change the font size and short tap will act as a mouse click. Long tap will toggle a text selection and the context menu.

Alpine Term provides a fixed amount of persistent non-closeable terminal sessions. Each of them has specific purpose. The first session is the QEMU monitor which gives you full control over VMâ€™s internal state.

Other four sessions are serial lines (ttyS0 - ttyS3) providing access to the operating system. As stated before, amount of sessions is fixed. To have more shell sessions you need a terminal multiplexor such as tmux.

Touch keyboard shortcuts

Volume Down button emulates Ctrl key which can be combined with others to request a special action from command line tools. Common key combinations are:

  • Ctrl+A â†’ Move cursor to the beginning of line
  • Ctrl+C â†’ Interrupt the current process with SIGINT
  • Ctrl+D â†’ Send end-of-file to the standard input
  • Ctrl+E â†’ Move cursor to the end of line
  • Ctrl+K â†’ Delete text from cursor to the end of line
  • Ctrl+L â†’ Clear the terminal
  • Ctrl+Z â†’ Suspend the current process with SIGTSTP

Volume Up key is used to to produce certain input on the following combinations:

  • Volume Up+. â†’ Ctrl+\ (SIGQUIT)
  • Volume Up+1 â†’ F1 (and Volume Up+2 â†’ F2, etc)
  • Volume Up+0 â†’ F10
  • Volume Up+A â†’ Left arrow key
  • Volume Up+B â†’ Alt+B, back a word (if using readline)
  • Volume Up+D â†’ Right arrow key
  • Volume Up+E â†’ Escape key
  • Volume Up+F â†’ Alt+F, forward a word (if using readline)
  • Volume Up+H â†’ ~ (the tilde character)
  • Volume Up+K â†’ Alias for Volume Up+Q
  • Volume Up+L â†’ | (the pipe character)
  • Volume Up+N â†’ Page Down
  • Volume Up+P â†’ Page Up
  • Volume Up+Q â†’ Toggle extra keys row
  • Volume Up+S â†’ Down arrow key
  • Volume Up+T â†’ Tab key
  • Volume Up+U â†’ _ (the underscore character)
  • Volume Up+V â†’ Show the volume control
  • Volume Up+W â†’ Up arrow key
  • Volume Up+X â†’ Alt+X

Note that Volume Up does not represent Alt key even though it is able to emulate some its combinations.

Hardware keyboard shortcuts

These keys in combination with Ctrl+Alt will trigger certain actions of Alpine Term when using a hardware keyboard:

  • +/- â†’ Adjust text size
  • 1-5 â†’ Go to the session with specified number
  • M â†’ Show the context menu
  • N â†’ Switch to the next session
  • P â†’ Switch to the previous session
  • U â†’ Open URL selector
  • V â†’ Paste clipboard
  • Left arrow â†’ Close drawer
  • Right arrow â†’ Open drawer
  • Down arrow â†’ Alias for N
  • Up arrow â†’ Alias for P

Usage tips

Booting Alpine Linux Live CD

You can boot from Live CD by choosing a DVD-ROM device from the boot menu which can be opened by tapping â€˜ESCâ€™ immediately when BIOS prompt appeared.

When you successfully booted the Alpine Linux Live CD, you will need to perform a basic system configuration by executing command â€˜setup-alpineâ€™. Otherwise you will not be able to install packages and available set of utilities will be quite small.

Connecting to host

You can access network services running on the host by connecting to IP 10.0.2.2.

For example if you have OpenSSH daemon running in Termux, you can simply execute

ssh -p 8022 10.0.2.2

in the VM and obtain shell access to the host.

Forwarding ports

To expose network services running inside the VM, open the QEMU monitor session (the top one in drawer) and execute a command having the next format:

hostfwd_add ${proto}::${ext_port}-:${int_port}

where:

  • ${proto} is either â€˜tcpâ€™ or â€˜udpâ€™.
  • ${ext_port} is a port that should be opened on host. Must be higher than 1024.
  • ${int_port} is a VM port being forwarded.

So, valid command for SSH will be:

hostfwd_add tcp::10022-:22

- all connections to the hostâ€™s port 10022 will be redirected to the port 22 in the VM.

Note that port redirects are removed when QEMU is being powered off. They also can be removed manually with â€˜hostfwd_removeâ€™. For example, the SSH port forwarding configured above can be disabled with:

hostfwd_remove tcp::10022

Increasing size of root partition

Alpine Term provides the disk image with maximal size of 128 GiB. However the root partition has size of 4 GiB to prevent the growing disk image from consuming all deviceâ€™s memory. You can extend the root partition with â€˜fdiskâ€™ as shown in this guide.

Steps that you need to perform:

  1. Determine a start sector. For image used with Alpine Term it is 2048.
  2. Determine initial size of the partition. Image default is 4096M.
  3. Delete the partition sda1.
  4. Create a new partition. You will be prompted for parameters.
    • Set partition type to primary (p).
    • Enter value 1 as partition number.
    • Enter value 2048 (same as in step 1) as first sector.
    • For last sector enter desired size of the new partition (for example +8G).
      Size should not be smaller than partitionâ€™s default (see step 2).
  5. Ensure that boot flag is turned on for the root partition.
  6. Write changes.

A transcript of â€˜fdiskâ€™ session for increasing root device size to 8 GiB:

There is nothing wrong with that, but this is larger than 1024,
and could in certain setups cause problems with:
1) software that runs at boot time (e.g., old versions of LILO)
2) booting and partitioning software from other OSs
   (e.g., DOS FDISK, OS/2 FDISK)

After finishing with fdisk you need to reboot. Then you will be able to resize file system according to the new size of partition (requires package â€˜e2fsprogs-extraâ€™):

resize2fs /dev/sda1

EXT4 file system supports online resizing and reboot is not needed at this step.

Pausing the VM

Stopping or resuming the VM execution is very simple. Just open the QEMU monitor session (the top one in drawer) and execute command stop - for pausing or cont - for resuming execution.

Pausing is useful if you want to keep Alpine Term running but have QEMU being idle, for example to prevent battery consumption when application is not used.

Saving and restoring the VM state

With VM snapshots you will be able to rollback changes made to the disk image. This feature is useful if you are experimenting with packages or configuration and do not want to reset the Alpine Term application in case if something went wrong.

Highly advisable to make a snapshot immediately after the first login.

Before making snapshot, ensure that host storage is not mounted:

umount /mnt/shared

- that is if you have not changed the default mount point in the /etc/fstab. Just QEMU does not allow saving state with VirtFS mounts, so this step is essential.

To save the virtual machine state, execute the next command in the monitor session:

savevm your_snapshot_name

Created snapshots may be loaded at any time with the next command:

loadvm your_snapshot_name

Note that both commands will freeze console during operation. Do not interrupt application until operation will not be finished.

Sharing files between host and VM

Alpine Term provides the way for storing files on host storage. QEMU is configured to share the private directory of Alpine Term application with a guest operating system. Host directory is usually located at

/storage/emulated/0/Android/data/alpine.term

and is easily accessible from a file manager application.

By default, the VM mounts this directory as /mnt/shared but you may edit the /etc/fstab to mount it under a different path.

Android applies certain restrictions on the shared storage:

  • File ownership cannot be modified.
  • File permissions cannot be modified.
  • Binary execution is not allowed.
  • Special files like symlinks are not supported.

Warning: if you want to uninstall the Alpine Term, do not forget to move files from the hostâ€™s shared directory to a different place. Otherwise all its data will be lost.

Shutting down the VM

You can shut down the virtual machine and exit application with these ways:

  • Executing command quit in QEMU monitor for immediate exit. May leave HDD file system in inconsistent state.
  • Executing command system_powerdown in QEMU monitor to initiate OS shut down through ACPI.
  • Executing command poweroff in OS shell.

If application got stuck and does not respond for some reason, you will need to force stop it through Android OS settings.

Using the X Window System

You can run graphical programs in the VM but with a few restrictions:

  • Performance is very low. Some programs may load few minutes before opening.
  • Graphical output is performed through QEMUâ€™s the embedded VNC server.
  • No VNC TLS encryption support in the current QEMU build.
  • VNC server accepts only the US keyboard layout.
  • You need a third-party program for connecting to the VNC server.
Setting up VNC

The VNC server is disabled by default. It can be enabled in the monitor session (the top one in drawer).

change vnc 127.0.0.1:1

The command shown above will start the VNC server on localhost and port 5901 (VNC port is determined from 5900 + display number).

Optionally you can enable a password authentication with these commands:

change vnc 127.0.0.1:1,password
change vnc password

Warning: password length is limited to 8 characters by the VNC protocol.

Setting up Xorg

Run a script provided by Alpine Linux to setup Xorg installation:

setup-xorg-base

Then you may install any additional software like window managers or utilities. For example:

apk add fluxbox gimp

Certain packages (like GIMP) require the TTF fonts which you may need to install manually:

apk add ttf-dejavu

When you are ready to launch your graphical environment, execute:

startx

Then check output in VNC client. If above command failed, you need to inspect a log file of the X server.

Common Xorg & VNC issues:

  1. Program may print an error about display opening failure. Should be solved by this command:

    export DISPLAY=:0

    If program still fails, make sure that Xorg is running.

  2. When launching GIMP or other program using D-Bus, it may complain about missing machine-id. You can generate it with this command:

    dbus-uuidgen > /var/lib/dbus/machine-id

  3. If your VNC client application shows an error:

    • Ensure that VNC server is running.
    • Ensure that you are connecting to the right port.
    • Try a different VNC client.
